#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:10
msgid "Part I Summary: The Core Bottleneck and the Path Forward"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:12
msgid ""
"The prerequisite knowledge established in <b>Part I</b> forms the "
"conceptual backbone for understanding Boltzmann machines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:13
msgid ""
"<b>Statistical Physics </b>provided the Boltzmann distribution, linking "
"low energy to high probability, and introduced the energy landscape "
"metaphor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:14
msgid ""
"<b>Neural network fundamentals</b> supplied the architectural building "
"blocks (units, biases, weights) and the biological inspiration (Hebbian "
"learning)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:15
msgid ""
"<b>Energy-Based Models</b> formalized the learning objective: shape the "
"energy function so that real data occupies deep valleys. The gradient "
"involves an expectation under the model distribution, which is "
"intractable to compute exactly due to the partition function sum over "
"exponentially many configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:16
msgid ""
"<b>Boltzmann Machine Architecture </b>evolved  from the computationally "
"prohibitive full Boltzmann Machine to the Restricted Boltzmann Machine "
"(RBM), which serves as the critical building block for stacking deep "
"generative architectures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:18
msgid "<b>The Core Tension: Expressiveness vs. Sampling Tractability</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:20
msgid ""
"Despite architectural simplifications, all Boltzmann machines share a "
"fundamental bottleneck: <b>sampling from high‑dimensional Boltzmann "
"distributions is hard</b>. Classical Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) "
"methods, such as Gibbs sampling, suffer from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:22
msgid ""
"<b>Slow mixing</b> at low temperatures, where energy barriers trap the "
"chain in isolated modes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:23
msgid ""
"<b>Mode collapse</b> in short‑run approximations like Contrastive "
"Divergence (CD)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:24
msgid ""
"<b>Bias</b> that accumulates when persistent chains fail to fully "
"equilibrate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:26
msgid ""
"This is not merely a software optimisation problem; it is a <b>physical "
"phenomenon</b> deeply rooted in statistical mechanics. Near a critical "
"point, correlation lengths diverge, causing the Markov chain to mix "
"extremely slowly (critical slowing down). The same physics that makes it "
"hard to simulate a critical Ising model also makes it hard to sample from"
" a well-trained Boltzmann machine that has learned a rich, multimodal "
"data distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:28
msgid ""
"These sampling limitations cap the practical expressiveness of "
"energy‑based models and motivate the search for fundamentally different "
"sampling strategies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:30
msgid "<b>A Principled Classical Alternative: Simulated Annealing</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:32
msgid ""
"<b>Simulated annealing (SA)</b> is a classical metaheuristic that can be "
"used to sample from Ising Hamiltonians. Instead of relying on a single "
"Markov chain, SA mimics the physical annealing process:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:34
msgid ""
"Start at a high temperature, allowing the system to explore the energy "
"landscape freely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:35
msgid "Gradually lower the temperature according to a cooling schedule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:36
msgid ""
"At each temperature, perform Metropolis updates to move toward low-energy"
" configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:38
msgid ""
"When the system is cooled sufficiently slowly, the final distribution of "
"states approximates the Boltzmann distribution at the effective "
"temperature. SA is a powerful baseline for sampling in Boltzmann machines"
" and is implemented in the `Kaiwu-PyTorch-Plugin` as the "
"`SimulatedAnnealingOptimizer`. It requires no specialized hardware and "
"can be run entirely on CPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:40
msgid ""
"However, SA still relies on <b>thermal activation</b> to escape local "
"minima, which becomes exponentially slow for high energy barriers (the "
"critical slowing down phenomenon). This limitation opens the door to more"
" advanced methods, including quantum sampling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:42
msgid "<b>Beyond Classical Sampling: Quantum Sampling </b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:44
msgid ""
"<b>Quantum sampling</b> offers a physically grounded alternative that can"
" overcome the limitations of classical MCMC and simulated annealing. "
"Instead of simulating a Markov chain, one can encode the energy function "
"as an Ising Hamiltonian and let a quantum physical system evolve toward "
"its low‑energy states. Devices such as <b>quantum annealers</b>,<b> "
"</b>i.e. Coherent Ising Machines (CIMs), realize this principle in "
"hardware."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:46
msgid ""
"The full details of quantum sampling, including its physical "
"implementation, integration with PyTorch, and practical performance "
"benefits, are <b>covered in the hands‑on tutorials of Part II</b>. You "
"will learn how to replace the classical `SimulatedAnnealingOptimizer` "
"with a quantum sampler (e.g., `CIMOptimizer`) and observe the potential "
"speed‑up and improved sample quality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:48
msgid "<b>Part II Preview: Quantum‑Enhanced Hands‑on Tutorials</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:50
msgid ""
"Part II [KPP Hands-on Tutorials](/kpp-hand-on-tutorials) shifts from "
"theory to practice. you will use the <b>Kaiwu-PyTorch-Plugin</b> to "
"replace classical sampling (Gibbs, CD, and simulated annealing) with "
"quantum‑enhanced sampling. The plugin abstracts away the hardware "
"details, allowing you to switch between classical and quantum samplers "
"with minimal code changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:52
msgid "Moreover, four sophisticated tasks will be covered:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:54
msgid ""
"<b>Quantum Sampling for EBMs:</b> Understand the annealing principle and "
"integrate quantum samplers into PyTorch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:55
msgid ""
"<b>Full Boltzmann Machine:</b> Model a 2D mixture distribution and "
"observe quantum speed‑up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:56
msgid ""
"<b>RBMs and DBNs: </b>Learn hierarchical features from MNIST digits; "
"compare quantum‑accelerated training against classical CD."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:57
msgid ""
"<b>Quantum Variational Autoencoder (Q‑VAE):</b> Replace the Gaussian "
"prior of a VAE with a discrete quantum RBM and apply it to image "
"generation and single‑cell transcriptomics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-recap.md:59
msgid ""
"Each tutorial is self‑contained in a Jupyter notebook that you can run, "
"modify, and extend. By the end of Part II, you will have experienced "
"first‑hand how quantum sampling alleviates the classical mixing "
"bottleneck and enables more expressive generative models."
msgstr ""

